SIMPLE: refuge
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Refuge
<hw>Ref"uge</hw> <pr>(r?f"?j)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧fuge</ets>, L. <ets>refugium</ets>, fr.
<ets>refugere</ets> to flee back; pref. <ets>re-</ets> +
<ets>figere</ets>. SEe <er>Fugitive</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Shelter or protection from danger or
distress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rocks, dens, and caves! But I in none of these⟦br⟧
Find place or <qex>refuge</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We might have a strong consolation, who have fled for
<qex>refuge</qex> to lay hold upon the hope set before us.</q>
<rj><qau>Heb. vi. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which shelters or protects from danger, or from
distress or calamity; a stronghold which protects by its strength, or a
sanctuary which secures safety by its sacredness; a place inaccessible
to an enemy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The high hills are a <qex>refuge</qex>r the wild goats.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. civ. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord also will be a <qex>refuge</qex> for the oppressed.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. ix. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1209 --></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An expedient to secure protection or defense; a
device or contrivance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their latest <qex>refuge</qex>⟦br⟧
Was to send him.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Light must be supplied, among graceful<qex>refuges</qex>, by
terracing <?/<?/<?/ story in danger of darkness.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H.
Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cities of refuge</b></col> <fld>(Jewish Antiq.)</fld>,
<cd>certain cities appointed as places of safe refuge for persons who
had committed homicide without design. Of these there were three on each
side of Jordan.</cd> <au>Josh. xx.</au> -- <col><b>House of
refuge</b></col>, <cd>a charitable institution for giving shelter and
protection to the homeless, destitute, or tempted.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Shelter; asylum; retreat; covert.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refuge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Refuge
<hw>Ref"uge</hw> <pr>(r?f"?j)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To shelter; to
protect.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refugee</ent>⟦br⟧
